🌶️SPICE UP THAT CORE ROUTINE🌶️

Bringing y’all some untraditional core pieces to add to your routine and get you thinking outside the box.

 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ 
1. Back planks: these are a great way to strengthen your back muscles. These muscles are active in nearly every activity you do, so we must keep them strong! We often train our abs, but how often do you train the opposite side? 🤔

2. Sand bag marching: these are a great way to challenge the abdominal wall via bracing. Squeeze the bag as you breath outward to create a barrel effect.

3. KB dead bugs: these are a great way to train your core stabilizers and bracing mechanics while adding a dynamic component to the movement. Bracing is important because it’s needed for everything we do in and out of the gym!

4. Mixed grip carries: these are great for challenging the muscles surrounding the spine and core. The variation of weight placement forces the body to adjustment and stabilize. 
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

⌛️IT TAKES TIME⌛️
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ 

As much as we’d all like to think that change is overnight, it’s not. True change takes time and time is what most of us think we don’t have. The reality is, we have plenty of time to make the change necessary to reach our goals and ambitions, particularly around health and wellness. 

To be more specific, I am narrowing this topic around our nutrition. I too thought that eating right or properly fueling my body would take too much time. Weighing my food and measuring my amounts all seemed overwhelming. Actually the time I spent complaining about being so far from my goals took more time than getting started. It wasn’t until I started that I noticed it’s more efficient than guessing or wondering what I was eating. The change in my sleep, energy, and performance was most noticeable, followed by aesthetics. To me, this made all the time I spent worth it and made me realize the mundane work is what leads us to our goals.

So if you’re on the fence about making a change because you fear the duration, take a leap of faith and remember any change takes time. The longer it takes to come the longer it will last.

CHANGE IS INEVITABLE
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ 

And it’s not usually easy, most of the time it’s not by choice or by preference. Move #3 in the books for us and it seems it’s getting harder and harder to adjust. Wanting to be closed off, wanting to allow the time to pass has been our normal. Wanting to go back to what was and thinking it’ll never be the same is painful. Over the last few years we have realized that the saying of “being where your feet are” is more true now than ever. Focusing on the only things you can control in your life is going to give you a sense of comfort momentarily, it’s going to give you a sense of normalcy. You are going to find out more about you during change than you will any other time. Give yourself permission to feel angry, sadness, frustration and happiness. There is no right way to feel, the only certainty is you have to adapt to whatever your current situation is.
 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ 
So here I am again, taking on another change, another reset, another opportunity to connect and grow but not alone.I am extremely fortunate enough to have loving people in my corner( my people) to give moments of bliss and fulfillment during this ride. I hope to continue bringing you all my best education, influence and authenticity during this continued journey.

💥CORE STABILITY💥
-
 Top of the weekend fam. Heres a dope collab with my bro @brickbuiltstrength focusing on foundation work. Core stability movements to really challenge your body and improve your game. 
-
THE WORK 🔨: 

1: ELEVATED BRIDGE LEG DROPS (POSTERIOR CHAIN)
2: BRIDGE CONTRALATERAL EXTENSIONS (POSTERIOR CHAIN)
3: ANTI FLEXION HOLDS 
4: BRDIGE MARCHES + ANTI ROTATION HOLDS 
5: MODIFIED OFFSET BB MARCHES 
6: SPLIT STANCE ANTI ROTATION HOLDS 
7: OFFSET MARCHES 
-
🔑 KEY REMINDER:

Core stability should be able to achieve 3 things:

- stabilize the spine
- maintain optimal alignment between the pelvis and the spine
- prevent unwanted and compensatory movements of the pelvis/spine during movements of the extremities.

 Your ability to use your muscles to keep you in a stable position is so important, core stability helps take pressure off of the spine, improve function and enhance athletic performance. Let us know how you like these movements down below 👇🏽.

“Mindfully eating” I know this probably sounds like watching what you eat, quality foods, better choices (all of which are true). What I’m referring to is being mindful during your meals and enjoying your food. Not seeing how fast you can scarf down your food before you barely taste it. Rather slowing down and being present during your meal, tasting, chewing and enjoying each bite. For me I’ve made a conscience effort to set my phone down, chew each bite and taste my food and as crazy as it sounds it’s been so beneficial. I actually digest properly, I appreciate my food that I cooked and actually feel more satisfied at the end. I’m not saying you need to eat so slow your food gets cold lol but I am saying to actually enjoy it, put that phone on DND. If you’re looking for similar practices and guidance click the link in the bio and give @workingagainstgravity a try. #brickbuiltstrength #brickbybrick #wag #wagambassador #macros

Try this instead of a regular calf raise. 

A Pigeon toed calf raise (toe-in calf raises) is when you do a calf raise with your toes turned inward. 

➡️targets inner part of the calf muscle and creates a more balanced calf development if you’ve got bigger outer calves
➡️improves ankle mobility by moving the ankle joints in a different range of motion compared to regular calf raises
➡️strengthens the muscles that control foot positioning which can help with gait or foot alignment issues 
*️⃣bending your knees when doing a calf raise places more emphasis on the soleus muscle 

‼️Add the Toe Spacers for better balance and alignment. And add our Split Mobility Wedge to increase the deficit when lowering.
